Core Assumptions — Venue Manager Dashboard

Status: LOCKED (Do Not Violate)
Audience: Human developers + AI coding agents
Last updated: Feb 2026

1. Authentication & Identity

- Auth provider: Supabase Auth (email + password only).

- Session model: JWT-based sessions issued by Supabase.

- One venue per manager:

- Each authenticated user maps to exactly one venue via venue_managers.

- No multi-venue switching.

- No admin privileges:

- This dashboard is not a master admin panel.

- No cross-venue access, overrides, or impersonation features.

2. Venue Identity (CRITICAL)

- Venue ID is NEVER accepted from the client.

- venueId is derived ONLY from auth context, via:

- Supabase Auth → user_id

- venue_managers lookup

- Injected into ctx.venue by venueManagerProcedure

- Any code that reads venueId from request input is a security bug.

3. Database Access Rules

- All database access is server-side only.

- Client-side Supabase .from() calls are forbidden.

- All DB reads/writes go through:

- tRPC procedures

- Drizzle ORM

- Every venue manager procedure must use venueManagerProcedure.

- Direct SQL or service-role DB access from client code is forbidden.

4. Security Model

- Primary gatekeeper: venueManagerProcedure middleware.

- Secondary backstop: PostgreSQL Row Level Security (RLS).

RLS must remain enabled on all relevant tables:

- venue_managers

- venues

- transactions_log

- qs_config_days

- qs_config_hours

- audit_log (if enabled)

Application logic must not attempt to bypass RLS.

If tRPC logic fails, RLS must still protect the data.

5. Storage Model (MVP)

Bucket: venue-covers

Read access: Public (unauthenticated).

Write access: Authenticated users only, enforced by Storage RLS.

Upload model:

- Direct browser upload using Supabase anon key + user JWT session.

- No server-side proxy uploads for venue covers.

Path isolation:

- Files MUST be uploaded to {venue*id}/{timestamp}*{filename}.

- Storage RLS enforces that users can write only to their own venue folder.

Database stores only the storage path, never the full public URL.

Public URLs are derived at render time, not persisted.

6. Data Constraints & Performance

Transaction queries are capped server-side:

Max 1000 rows per request (hard limit).

Date range queries are capped:

Max 31 days per request.

Client attempts to exceed limits must be rejected or clamped server-side.

Polling model: React Query polling every 5 seconds.

Polling must pause when the browser tab is hidden.

No WebSockets for MVP.

7. Exports & Reporting

CSV exports are client-side only.

No server-side bulk exports for MVP.

Exported data must respect the same filters and RLS constraints.

8. Audit & Logging

Audit logging is optional for MVP, except:

Panic Off actions MUST be audited.

Audit entries must include:

- venue_id

- user_id

- action

- timestamp

- change payload (JSON)

9. Scope Boundaries

This dashboard is for venue managers only.

No patron features.

No master admin features.

No role escalation.

No background jobs or cron work in MVP unless explicitly planned.

10. Change Discipline (For Humans & AI)

If a feature conflicts with these assumptions, the assumptions win.

If implementation requires breaking an assumption:

STOP

Propose a plan change

Get explicit approval

“Just this once” exceptions are not allowed.

11. Single Sentence Rule (for agents)

If you cannot explain how a feature respects venue isolation, auth context, and RLS in one sentence, it is not ready to be implemented.
